\b MALWARE ANALYST:\par
\b0 A Malware analyst's work involves analysing suspicious programs, discovering what they do and writing reports about their findings. A malware analyst is sometimes called a reverse-engineer as their core task revolves around converting compiled programs from machine language to readable code, usually in a low-level language.\par
This work requires the malware analyst to have a strong programming background, especially in low-level languages such as assembly language and C language.\par
\par
\b Responsibilities\par
\b0 1. Carry out static analysis of malicious programs, which entails reverse-engineering.\par
2. Conduct dynamic analysis of malware samples by observing their activities in a controlled environment.\par
3. Document and report all the findings.\par
\par
\b PENETRATION TESTER\par
\b0 You may see penetration testing referred to as pentesting and ethical hacking. \par
A penetration tester's job role is to test the security of the systems and software within a company - this is achieved through attempts to uncover flaws and vulnerabilities through systemised hacking. \par
Penetration testers exploit these vulnerabilities to evaluate the risk in each instance. \par
The company can then take these insights to rectify issues to prevent a real-world cyberattack.\par
\par
\b Responsibilities\par
\b0 1. Conduct tests on computer systems, networks, and web-based applications.\par
2. Perform security assessments, audits, and analyse policies.\par
3. Evaluate and report on insights, recommending actions for attack prevention.\par
\par
\b RED TEAMERS:\par
\b0 The main difference between a Red Teamer and a penetration tester is their focus. \par
Penetration testers look for vulnerabilities in systems to help organizations improve their security, while Red Teamers simulate real-world attacks to test how well a company can detect and respond to threats. \par
Red Teamers often have a more targeted approach, acting like adversaries and assessing the organization's security controls over a longer period. Both roles are important, but they serve different purposes in strengthening security. Be sure to read the task details to continue progressing!\par
\b Responsibilities:\par
\b0 1. Emulate the role of a threat actor to uncover exploitable vulnerabilities, maintain access and avoid detection.\par
2. Assess organisations' security controls, threat intelligence, and incident response procedures.\par
3. Evaluate and report on insights, with actionable data for companies to avoid real-world instances.\b\par
